Taxi Rides Dataset

Data fields

  • id: a unique identifier for each trip
  • vendor_id - a code indicating the provider associated with the trip record
  • pickup_datetime - date and time when the meter was engaged
  • dropoff_datetime - date and time when the meter was disengaged
  • passenger_count - the number of passengers in the vehicle (driver entered value)
  • pickup_longitude - the longitude where the meter was engaged
  • pickup_latitude - the latitude where the meter was engaged
  • dropoff_longitude - the longitude where the meter was disengaged
  • dropoff_latitude - the latitude where the meter was disengaged
  • store_and_fwd_flag - This flag indicates whether the trip record was held in vehicle memory before sending to the vendor because the vehicle did not have a connection to the server - Y=store and forward; N=not a store and forward trip
  • trip_duration - duration of the trip in seconds

Our goal with the dataset is to predict the trip_duration depending on these variables.

Same for 1 second ride. Smth like a test maybe? Anyway we need to addres that. We'll use IQR for that.

In [310]:
q1 = df['trip_duration'].quantile(0.25)
q3 = df['trip_duration'].quantile(0.75)
IQR = q3-q1
lower_bound = q1-1.5*IQR
upper_bound = q3+1.5*IQR
outliers = df[(df['trip_duration'] < lower_bound) | (df['trip_duration'] > upper_bound)]

Feature engineering¶

We have some feature that look useles by themselves for the modelling or any analysis. Like datetime or geo coordinates - we can't get anything from them in that form. So we need to convert'em into something more convenient.

Distance¶

First we'll try to make a new feature - distance, as a predictor. Of course that's the approximation, not a real distance, it does not take into account turns.

For that we'll use geopy library.

In [316]:
import geopy.distance

# a reminder: 1st lat, then - long: (lat, long)

coords_1 = (40.767937, -73.982155)
coords_2 = (40.765602, -73.964630)

print(geopy.distance.geodesic(coords_1, coords_2).km)

geopy.distance.geodesic(
    (df_cleaned['pickup_latitude'][0], df_cleaned['pickup_longitude'][0]), 
    (df_cleaned['dropoff_latitude'][0], df_cleaned['dropoff_longitude'][0])
).km

In [317]:
# A tiny function to calculate distance

def distance(row):
    
    plat, plon, dlat, dlon = row
    return geopy.distance.geodesic(
        (plat, plon), 
        (dlat, dlon)
    ).km
In [318]:
# A subset with necessary features to calc. distance. Then we'll use the result for original df

sub_dist = df_cleaned[['pickup_latitude', 'pickup_longitude', 'dropoff_latitude', 'dropoff_longitude']]
sub_dist['distance'] = sub_dist.apply(lambda row: distance(row), axis=1)

Handlimg date time issue¶

pickup_datetime and dropoff_datetime features have date and time combined what makes them hard to work with. So just to see if these features can be valuable for us we'll decompose them.

In [321]:
# all features need to be extracted from orig. data if i want to use them in model
df_cleaned['pickup_hour'] = df_cleaned['pickup_datetime'].dt.hour
df_cleaned['pickup_day'] = df_cleaned['pickup_datetime'].dt.day
df_cleaned['pickup_month'] = df_cleaned['pickup_datetime'].dt.month
df_cleaned['pickup_weekday'] = df_cleaned['pickup_datetime'].dt.weekday

df_cleaned['dropoff_hour'] = df_cleaned['dropoff_datetime'].dt.hour
df_cleaned['dropoff_day'] = df_cleaned['dropoff_datetime'].dt.day
df_cleaned['dropoff_month'] = df_cleaned['dropoff_datetime'].dt.month
df_cleaned['dropoff_weekday'] = df_cleaned['dropoff_datetime'].dt.weekday
In [322]:
# now drop redundant data cols
df_cleaned = df_cleaned.drop(['pickup_datetime', 'dropoff_datetime'], axis=1)

Now we have new features: pickup and dropoff hour, day, month and day of the week.

These are the hours where Vendor 1 underperformes.

result = pd.concat([pvp, difference], axis=1)

The diff heatmap is more useful. Here the bright colors mean that Vendor 1 has advantage, dark cells show Vendor 2 has advantage.

There are more rides with Vendor 2 booked by larger groups - 5, 6 passengers in the evening and noon hours. But the vendor 2 severly underperformes for 1-passenger rides. Vendor 1 beats by number of shorter rides for smaller groups (1-2).

Both vendors don't have lots of customers for 3 to 4 passengers rides.

We see strong positive correlation between the new-made feature distance and trip_duration. But not strong enough to cause multicollinearity.

The longitude vars have stronger positive correlation with distance than lat vars that have slightly negative correlation, like if people for longer trips go more north-south than east-west. That aligns with the shape of the area.

Since we removed the outliers we need no more the log-transformed var for trip duration, especially considering that its coeff. of correlation with the duration is weaker than the original's coefficient. So before modelling we can remove it.

Modelling¶

In [333]:
def get_mae(model):

    y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train)
    y_test_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    
    # Eval on training set
    train_mse = mean_squared_error(y_train, y_train_pred)
    train_r2 = r2_score(y_train, y_train_pred)
    
    # Eval on test set
    test_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_test_pred)
    test_r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_test_pred)
    
    print('Train evaluation:')
    print(f'MSE: {train_mse:.4f}')
    print(f'RMSE: {(train_mse)**0.5:.4f}')
    print(f'R^2: {train_r2:.4f}')
    
    print('\nTest evaluation:')
    print(f'MSE: {test_mse:.4f}')
    print(f'RMSE: {(test_mse)**0.5:.4f}')
    print(f'R^2: {test_r2:.4f}')

R^2 is much better than with the baseline model.

This is a very small dataset, with only about 60,000 data points and a small number of variables. Within this dataset, it is unlikely to achieve a better R^2 score — these predictors are insufficient for building a better model. It would be possible to use external datasets, such as more precise geodata or data on trip costs.
